The problem is caused by an issue with Chromium based browsers. See https://stackoverflow.com/questions/50372849

Firefox runs your example correctly. Edge (as of this date not yet Chromium based) fails anyway because it regards all keydown&#39;s repeat properties as `false`. I don&#39;t know how Safari handles the example.

This can be seen using [Keyboard Event Tester](https://dvcs.w3.org/hg/d4e/raw-file/tip/key-event-test.html) and [Keyboard Event Viewer](http://w3c.github.io/uievents/tools/key-event-viewer.html) which display repeat values and other information as keys are pressed, held and released.

With Chromium in particular, after a keyup occurs while another repeating key is held, the held key&#39;s next keydown event will report its `.repeat` property once as `false`, and resumes to `true` for subsequent repeating events, thus causing an extra increment in the counter. Firefox maintains `true` throughout.

A workaround is to set a flag, `lastHeldKey`, that remembers the current/latest pressed key&#39;s `.code`, checking for a match at keydown in order to skip counter increment as if the `.repeat` were `true`, and checking for a match at keyup to reset/clear the flag in case the next keydown happens to be the same as the released key. If not a match at keyup then allow flag to remain with its latest keydown `.code` value.

    let pressedCount = 0,
      lastHeldKey = &#39;&#39;;
    $(document).keydown(function(event) {
      if (!event.originalEvent.repeat &amp;&amp; event.originalEvent.code != lastHeldKey) {
        lastHeldKey = event.originalEvent.code;
        pressedCount++;
        setCheck();
      }
    });
    $(document).keyup(function(event) {
      if (event.originalEvent.code == lastHeldKey) {
        lastHeldKey = &#39;&#39;;
      }
      pressedCount--;
      setCheck();
    });

